g.text: Suggestion: There's no sweet-talking your way in there. Be official.
Perception (Hearing): Sounded like a woman. A woman's shoes.
Half Light: Scare them. Suspected of some *big crime*!
Locked Door: The walking stops abruptly, but no one comes to the door.
Inland Empire: You can feel tension on the other side.
Locked Door: The door number #10 is closed again.
Locked Door: "Oh, come on!" There's a pause, before you hear the door being unlocked.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Let's go," the lieutenant says, "we don't have a reason to get inside that apartment."
Physical Instrument: Later then. Entering this door seems a physical *challenge*.
You: "I don't need a warrant if I suspect there's been a *break-in*."
Locked Door: Nothing happens. The real estate agent must have left.
Locked Door: You hear someone walking around inside, rearranging the furniture. The number on the panel says #10.
Locked Door: This time the steps come closer. "Who is this?" demands a female voice, wary and tense.
Locked Door: "Excuse me? Of course not!"
Logic: You have *plenty* of reason to enter.
Locked Door: "Do you have a warrant? I'm not obligated to open the door if you don't have a warrant."
Locked Door: "Do I *have to* open the door?" You hear the clacking of heels again, as the other side walks right up to the door. Her tone is now getting a defensive edge...
You: "Then open the door, so I can *verify* your identity."
You: "This is the police. Open up."
Kim Kitsuragi: "That was smart," the lieutenant says, nodding toward the unlocked door.
Logic: It's generally easier to do things if you have literally *any* reason.
You: "This apartment is supposed to be empty. Did you break in here?"
